<subSubSection id="49C942EEFFE2393AEBD2C3F4FCEF5EE0" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="016C1165FFE2393AEBD2C3F4FEAA5FD7" blockId="76.[227,341,1223,1249]" box="[227,341,1223,1249]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<heading id="5A24A609FFE2393AEBD2C3F4FEAA5FD7" bold="true" box="[227,341,1223,1249]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFE2393AEBD2C3F4FEAA5FD7" bold="true" box="[227,341,1223,1249]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FFE2393AEBD2C3C9FCEF5EE0" blockId="76.[225,1436,1273,1495]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
At a first glance, these small otoliths can be confused with the juveniles of “ 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FFE2393AEF7AC3C9FB635E22" box="[1099,1180,1274,1300]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sparidae" genus="Sparus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFE2393AEF7AC3C9FB635E22" box="[1099,1180,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Sparus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FFE2393AEF81C3CAFEDA5E0C" authority="(Koken, 1888)" baseAuthorityName="Koken" baseAuthorityYear="1888" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Otolithus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="elegantulus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFE2393AEF81C3CAFAC85E25" box="[1200,1335,1273,1299]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">elegantulus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FFE2393AEE74C3CAFEE25E0C" author="Koken" firstAuthor="Koken" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="274 - 305" refId="ref54599" refString="Koken E. 1888. Neue Untersuchungen an tertiaren Fisch-Otolithen. Zeitschrift der deutschen geologischen Gesellschaft 40: 274 - 305." type="journal article" year="1888">Koken, 1888</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(see below). Nevertheless, 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FFE2393AE95AC212FCE15E0C" authorityName="Nolf &amp; Stringer" authorityYear="2003" box="[619,798,1312,1339]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Centropristis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="priaboniana">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFE2393AE95AC212FCE15E0C" box="[619,798,1312,1339]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">C. priaboniana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a nearly horizontal ostial crista inferior, forming a triangular ostium, while in “ 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFE2393AE903C27BFDB75E54" box="[562,584,1352,1378]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">S.</emphasis>
” 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FFE2393AE96FC274FD1A5E57" baseAuthorityName="Koken" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[606,741,1351,1377]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Otolithus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="elegantulus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFE2393AE96FC274FD1A5E57" box="[606,741,1351,1377]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">elegantulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the ostial crista inferior is evenly widened like that of the crista superior and forms an oval ostium. Otoliths of 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FFE2393AE87FC25CFBFE5EBE" authorityName="Nolf &amp; Stringer" authorityYear="2003" box="[846,1025,1390,1417]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Centropristis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="priaboniana">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFE2393AE87FC25CFBFE5EBE" box="[846,1025,1390,1417]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">C. priaboniana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are rare (n = 5), but our specimens from the Moodys Branch Formation, 
<collectingRegion id="C317DF87FFE2393AE9A4C2A6FCE45E99" box="[661,795,1429,1455]" country="United States of America" name="Mississippi" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Mississippi</collectingRegion>
expands their record to a lower level than their original 
<typeStatus id="DE68AFC7FFE2393AEBD3C28EFEEA5EE1" box="[226,277,1469,1495]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">type</typeStatus>
locality from the Yazoo Clay of 
<collectingRegion id="C317DF87FFE2393AE9A4C28FFCF25EE0" box="[661,781,1468,1494]" country="United States of America" name="Louisiana" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Louisiana</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
